Editorial
The last line
In the last two years I have participated directly in
the production of over sixth issues of the charles & Black
. . . some 500 pages altogether. This is the last and I am
had, but it it were mine to do over again, I would not
private. dirty weeks . . . maybe 1,000 hours. Perhaps, I
can best conclude by trying as best I can to tell why.
Why? is seldom an easy question to answer. This is
no exception. I could as easily tell why live, for the answer
is much the same.
It goes beyond a commitment to journalism. Journalism is no sacred cow of mine. It goes beyond a desire to
correct the failures of Grinnell College. Though this is perhaps part of the answer. Ultimately, I suppose, editing the
8&3, is part of search. A search which I share with my
classified and probably with every other generation that
was once young and idealistic. A search for harmony and
meaning in the lives of men.
In a world like all human worlds, filled with democracy and hate, is there no way in which men can live in
poverty and love‘.7 Is there no way in which individual
good is compatible with common good. cannon communities and nationalism give way to humanity. Must some
men always die that others may live.
The particular tool I have brought to my search is
a typewriter. There is no end to other approaches. The only
absolute seems to be that the search must he made. In
a nuclear world we canon share Frost’s unconcern:
A111 worry about is the sun ‘
We’ll be tonight if nothing goes wrong With the
lighting
If we continue to fail in our search, Bob Dylan may have
come closer to the truth:
It’s a hard gains a gonna fall.
