Faculty Comment
A Crime" Dilemma
By EZRA MENDELSOHN
history
I have been asked by the charles and Black to
comment on the question oi student sexual moral<
its. 1 claim no special knowledge which would allow me to speak with certainly on this complex
subject. but I believe that my recent arrival at:
Grinnell gives me a fresh perspective. I welcome
any response to my observations and suggestions,
for it. is clear that a continuing discussion is necessary lot the establishment and maintenance or
harmony among some students, faculty, and administration.
One response to the debate over limitation and
women’s hours is simply to concern all student
premarital sex. it is imitlcss to argue with
people who sincerely hold this position, just as it
is stainless to argue with concern systems that
Mohammad was not the prophet oi Allah. it is my
assumption, however, that premarital sex is not
necessarily harmful or removal; it is likewise my
assumption that students who engage in such ac.
entities at Grinnell should not feel that they are
commitment an illegal act which, it brought to the
attention of the authorities, will result in severe
penalties.
To be sure, the problem is greater here in a
small, midwestem, Christian Community than it
would be elsewhere. I have been part of academic
communities in New York, Philadelphia. and
Israel. At each of these places either the instead<
tion was more liberal with regard to the sexual
behavior of its students than Grinnell, or the location itself provided the opportunity to enjoy a
relatively free social lite. But it is just because
Grinnell is what it is that we need to be more imagination in solving our problems. On the one
hand, wo-‘have intelligent and, i think, fairly so
complicated students, attempted to Grinnell because
ot its high academic standing. 0n the other hand,
we live in a narrow social environment. Concerts,
athletics. the occasional touring theater or opera
company are comfortable in themselves, but we
all know that we ultimately spend a very small
percentage of our leisure lime attending these
functions. What most of us want to do (and I assume that Grinnell students like no exception) is
to talk, eat, and drink with our friends. We are
not going to sleep with every person with whom
we become friendly. We may not even wish to
sleep with those whom we love. But we are all
made to feel guilty in a system which treaty limitations as “occasions for sin," and we are all
made to feel uncomfortable in a system which im-
posts strict regulations and then rapidly ag es not
to efforts these regulations as long as issues
tion” is maintained. 1
1 know that the common reply to the occupation that it is hypocri 'cal to have rules which are
discretion ignored is. “You have more freedom
now than you would it the rules were informed."
And I am aware of the criticism made of the
students that. by their protest, they only imposed
the eventual relaxation of regulations. The first
statement can scarcely be deferred. As for the
second point, it seems to me that the students, by
making their meetings known in a restricted and
responsible fashion, achieved car more than they
lost. 1 take their action to be a sign of majority,
rather than the reverse, and I think it is a highly
encouraging sign that Grinnell students are thinking not only of their exams and papers, but of
other problems as well.
Assuming that the students are sincerely up<
set by the lack of freedom which characterized the
Situation at Grinnell, can We hope that faculty
and administration will be more respective to
their needs in the future? Can’t we make a lists
ing contribution to this whole question by thinking in terms of building new directories, which
would provide decent sitting room: for small,
informal parties? Can‘t we allow more upper
classics (and women) to live oftcampus, it
they wish? Can’t we relax limitation recreational,
And can’t. we think in terms at establishing
oil-campus social clubs, so that students might
occasionally escape from the familiar (sometimes
all too familiar) atmosphere of the College?
The essential question, perhaps, is whether
Grinnell is to follow, or to lead. A“! we of the
faculty and the administration prepared to take
certain risks in order to create a more healthy
situation at the College? And, no less important,
are the Students prepared to accept new responsibilities (after all, greater freedom impose‘
greater responsibilities)? We know, in these postFreudian days. that sex cannon be sweet under
the table. or snblimsted by means of fifty mile
bikes through scenic Iowa. We know that a
healthy attitude towards sex, one which record
sizes its tremendous potential for both unselfishness and harm, is dependent upon attitudes towards authority, both parental and institutional.
Let me close with a plea that the whole question or student sexual mobility be explorer knew
in the true spa 't of iniellectualism.
I stand with a famous 19in century thunder,
who appendix to one of his creatures: “Dixi et
salvavi animal team.”
 
